def run_statistical_tests():
    from scipy import stats
    df = df_features if df_features is not None else (df_clean if df_clean is not None else df_raw)
    num_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()
    cat_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns.tolist()
    
    # Test 1: Normality test on first numeric column
    if len(num_cols) >= 1:
        col = num_cols[0]
        stat, p = stats.shapiro(df[col].dropna().head(5000))
        print(f'Normality Test ({col}): p-value = {p:.4f}')
    
    # Test 2: Correlation test between first two numeric columns
    if len(num_cols) >= 2:
        col1, col2 = num_cols[0], num_cols[1]
        r, p = stats.pearsonr(df[col1].dropna(), df[col2].dropna())
        print(f'Correlation Test ({col1} vs {col2}): r={r:.4f}, p-value={p:.4f}')
    
    # Test 3: Group comparison if categorical column exists
    if len(cat_cols) >= 1 and len(num_cols) >= 1:
        cat_col, num_col = cat_cols[0], num_cols[0]
        groups = [group[num_col].dropna() for name, group in df.groupby(cat_col)]
        if len(groups) >= 2:
            stat, p = stats.kruskal(*groups[:5])  # Limit to 5 groups
            print(f'Group Comparison ({num_col} by {cat_col}): p-value = {p:.4f}')

# Executive Summary
The dataset, initially comprising 62,988 records and 23 columns, underwent extensive cleaning and feature engineering, addressing missing values and creating new interaction features. Analysis revealed strong positive correlations among key customer activity metrics and spending, indicating robust relationships crucial for customer segmentation. The data is now prepared for machine learning, with scaled numerical features and one-hot encoded categorical variables, making it suitable for clustering or predictive modeling tasks.

## Data Overview
